## How the Computer Sees Data

#### Unlike humans, computers need to store and process data differently.

<div style="background-color: #F5F7F8; color: #000000; padding: 15px; border-radius: 10px; width: 90%; margin: 20px auto;">
        <p style="font-size: 14pt; line-height: 1.2; margin-top: 10px;">
        <ul>
    <li style="font-size: 14pt;"><b>Whole numbers</b> (integers) can be used for counting.<br></li><br>
    <li style="font-size: 14pt;"><b>Text </b>(strings) stores names and addresses.<br></li><br>
    <li style="font-size: 14pt;"><b>True/False values </b> (booleans) help make decisions.<br></li><br>
    <li style="font-size: 14pt;"><b>Decimal numbers</b> (doubles) store values that are not whole, like prices or measurements.<br></li>
</ul>
    </p>
</div>


#### A computer organizes these into different types because it processes them differently.

## Introducing Variable Types 

#### In Java, we store data in variables. But depending on the type of data, we choose different variable types and define them when declaring the variable:

<img src="https://images.code.org/71635f4c12a0634325422d955ef60a66-image-1747324184467.png" alt="sample code of declaring variable types in Java" width="450px" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;">

#### Different variable types allow Java to handle data properly. Integers can be used for math, strings store text, booleans hold True/False values, and doubles handle decimal numbers.

<br>

## Let's explore more! 
